### Generic Methods in C#

Generic methods have type parameters listed in angle brackets. They can exist in non-generic classes.

### Basic Generic Method

```csharp
public static T DisplayAndReturn<T>(T value)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Value: {value}");
    return value;
}

// Usage
int result = DisplayAndReturn(42);
string text = DisplayAndReturn("Hello");
```

### Type Inference

The compiler can infer type parameters from arguments:

```csharp
// Explicit
int max = FindMax<int>(5, 10);

// Inferred (cleaner)
int max = FindMax(5, 10);
double maxVal = FindMax(3.14, 2.71);

static T FindMax<T>(T a, T b) where T : IComparable<T>
{
    return a.CompareTo(b) > 0 ? a : b;
}
```

### Generic Methods with Constraints

```csharp
public static void ProcessItems<T>(List<T> items) where T : class
{
    foreach (var item in items)
        Console.WriteLine(item?.ToString() ?? "null");
}
```

### Multiple Type Parameters

```csharp
public static Dictionary<TKey, TValue> CreateDictionary<TKey, TValue>
    (TKey key, TValue value) where TKey : notnull
{
    return new Dictionary<TKey, TValue> { { key, value } };
}

var dict = CreateDictionary("key1", 42);
```

### Generic Method in Non-Generic Class

```csharp
public static class ArrayHelper
{
    public static T[] CreateAndFill<T>(int size, T value)
    {
        T[] array = new T[size];
        Array.Fill(array, value);
        return array;
    }

    public static void Swap<T>(ref T a, ref T b)
    {
        T temp = a;
        a = b;
        b = temp;
    }
}

// Usage
int[] tens = ArrayHelper.CreateAndFill(5, 10);
int x = 1, y = 2;
ArrayHelper.Swap(ref x, ref y);
```

### Generic Extension Methods

```csharp
public static class Extensions
{
    public static T? GetRandomElement<T>(this IEnumerable<T> source)
    {
        var list = source.ToList();
        if (list.Count == 0) return default;
        return list[Random.Shared.Next(list.Count)];
    }
}
```

### Method Type Inference Rules

| Rule | Example |
|------|---------|
| Inferred from parameters | `Foo(42)` infers `int` |
| Cannot infer from return only | `var x = Foo<int>()` requires explicit |
| Mixed inference | `Foo<int>(42, "text")` partial |

> **Key Point:** The compiler infers generic type parameters from method arguments when possible. Use constraints to restrict what types can be used. Generic methods work in both generic and non-generic classes. Type inference makes calling code cleaner.

### Generic Method Overloading

```csharp
static void Process<T>(T item) { }
static void Process<T1, T2>(T1 a, T2 b) { }
static void Process<T>(T item, int count) where T : class { }
```

### Performance Note

Generic methods are specialized at runtime for each value type but share a single implementation for reference types.

codeExample:
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        var numbers = new List<int> { 3, 1, 4, 1, 5 };
        var words = new List<string> { "apple", "banana", "cherry" };

        Console.WriteLine($"First number: {GetFirstOrDefault(numbers)}");
        Console.WriteLine($"First word: {GetFirstOrDefault(words)}");
        Console.WriteLine($"Empty list: {GetFirstOrDefault(new List<double>())}");
    }

    static T? GetFirstOrDefault<T>(List<T> list)
    {
        return list.Count > 0 ? list[0] : default;
    }
}
